AB  - To provide a comprehensive analysis of the Otago Exercise Program (OEP) that examines whether participation produces an enhancement in mood state. Secondary objective was to explore the motivational factors for initiating and maintaining physical activity behavior, particularly within the context of the Otago program. Mixed-methods: (1) Quantitative (n=30): Profile of Mood States (POMS) before, after, and 24 hours after the OEP; (2) Qualitative (n=5): individual, semistructured interviews identifying facilitator/barrier themes. The OEP is an evidence-based program, which consists of 5 warm-up exercises and 17 strength and balance exercises that are performed 3 times a week by older adults in the home, outpatient, or community setting. Community sites where Otago exercise classes were held. A random sample of participants (N=30) age 60 years or older, low to moderate assessed fall risk and living independently in the community. Not applicable. Profile of Mood States and facilitator/barrier themes. Multivariate repeated-measures analysis of variance showed significant improvement for tension, vigor, confusion, and the total mood disturbance (TMD) score (P <.05) after the OEP. Twenty-four hours later vigor, confusion, and TMD (P <.05) still showed significant improvement. No significant differences were observed in depression, anger, and fatigue (P >.05) after the OEP. Systematic text condensation, emphasized that commitment, obligation, and achievement were motivational in initiating physical activity, whereas poor health, unattained goals, and disengagement were barriers. Results indicate that the OEP produces an enhancement in mood state, particularly in reducing tension, enhancing vigor, and reducing confusion. The study also contributes knowledge on multiple facilitators and barriers to exercise, specifically the OEP, which can inform strategies to support older adults in initiating and maintaining physical activity behaviors. The Otago Exercise Program received funding from Region VII Area Agency on Aging. Institutional IRB provided an exempt determination. We are declaring no conflicts of interest. ABSTRACT FROM AUTHOR
