AB  - Men who experience intimate partner violence and abuse (IPVA) are at risk of significant health and social consequences. However, many remain without sufficient professional support due to unique challenges in the help-seeking process. It is unclear whether gender-neutral interventions can adequately support men with IPVA experiences or whether gender-specific approaches are required. Moreover, relevant components and contents of psychosocial support for men experiencing IPVA remain vague. This study examines client characteristics that must be considered when providing psychosocial support to men experiencing IPVA and gathers recommendations for the design of adequate support services. We conducted semistructured interviews with 14 international service providers who work with men affected by IPVA in specialized counseling and mental health settings. We analyzed the data using qualitative content analysis. Our findings corroborate gender-typical characteristics of men experiencing IPVA that must be considered by psychosocial support, including gender-typical forms of IPVA experienced, help-seeking challenges, and support preferences. Additionally, adequate support must consider individual characteristics of the client, including the client’s current stage, involvement of children, concurrent psychological disorders, polyvictimization experiences, bidirectional IPVA, and intersectional aspects. Consequently, our findings suggest that psychosocial support services for men experiencing IPVA must be both, gender-sensitive and individualized. We identified critical components and essential topics of psychosocial support for men experiencing IPVA, which may assist practitioners in implementing appropriate services. Sufficient funding, training, and improved service structures appear to be essential to ensure the quality of care. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2026 APA, all rights reserved)
