AB  - Scientific and anecdotal evidence points to a relationship between arts and humanities (A&H) engagement and flourishing across multiple dimensions, yet this relationship among Black Americans has been underexplored. The study surveyed 596 Black Americans to examine demographic differences in A&H engagement, motivations behind A&H engagement, associations with participant’s psychological, collective, and transcendent flourishing, and the mechanisms (e.g., immersion, socialization, and expression) by which A&H may lead to flourishing. Results showed demographic differences in A&H domain participation by age, income, education, and gender. Results of multiple regression analyses showed cognitive, social, and activism motivations were associated with multiple aspects of flourishing. Our findings suggest a link between engagement in certain A&H domains and particular flourishing outcomes and mechanisms of individual engagement in A&H and collective and transcendent flourishing. Studies have also shown lower visitation at arts institutions by Black Americans, so the present research also explored barriers to A&H participation and queried what factors make Black Americans feel welcome in an arts space. Upon quantitatively examining barriers to participation, we found that high costs and long distances were among the most strongly endorsed reasons for not attending arts events despite interest. Qualitative analysis of visible and invisible indicators of welcome revealed that participants felt both physical signs—such as the presence of inclusive flags—and nonphysical signs—such as a sense of belonging fostered by diverse visitors and artwork—would increase feelings of inclusion in arts spaces. These results underscore the need to understand the role of arts engagement in the flourishing of Black Americans. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
