AB  - The article focuses on the perceptions of university mental health counselors regarding the prescription of physical activity to students experiencing mental health issues, particularly anxiety and depression. A qualitative study involving 14 certified counselors from seven southern universities revealed that while counselors are generally open to prescribing physical activity and referring students to specialists, they feel that additional formal training is necessary to do so effectively. The findings suggest that referring students to trained physical activity specialists is currently seen as a more feasible option than direct prescription. Future research is recommended to quantitatively assess the effectiveness of these referrals on improving students' physical activity levels and mental health outcomes. Extracted from the article
