AB  - Across Canada, more allied health professionals are providing evidence-based psychotherapies (EBPs). EBPs are effective, time-limited psychological interventions. However, clients’ response to these EBPs can depend on the providers’ prior training, adherence to, and competence in these specific treatments. However, we did not know the extent that allied health professionals currently receive training in psychotherapy principles and specific EBPs in their academic programs in Canada. Our primary objective is to understand what exposure mental health professionals receive to EBPs in postsecondary programs, prior to entering the workforce. We reviewed program requirements of n = 290 accredited academic programs across six mental health-related disciplines: clinical psychology, counselling, occupational therapy, social work, nursing, and general medicine. We independently coded publicly available program materials (i.e., websites, brochures) to identify applied training (e.g., practicum training during the academic program) and coursework (i.e., general psychotherapy, specific EBP courses, multicultural/diversity psychotherapy). Finally, we also reviewed qualitative responses from a small sample of training directors. Most programs required some applied training; however, only a quarter required psychotherapy training. As for coursework, about half of the programs coded had at least one general psychotherapy course, far fewer offered courses in EBPs, and even less had courses considering multicultural/diversity psychotherapy. Given the limitations of our methodology, these findings should be replicated. However, there is likely a gap between students receiving EBP training and professionals providing EBPs in their careers. Therefore, training programs may consider adjusting their curricula to meet the changing mental health landscape in Canada. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
