AB  - Stress-management training for leaders may not only enhance the well-being of the leaders themselves but it is also thought to impact their employees. Currently, there is limited evidence demonstrating the beneficial effects of leader stress-management training on employee well-being or distress. Therefore, we implemented a stress-management intervention for leaders and tested for indirect crossover effects on their employees. We conducted a quasi-experimental study and collected well-being data from leaders and their employees at baseline, as well as 6 and 12 months after the intervention. A total of 75 leaders and 322 employees participated in the survey. Results were analyzed using mixed-effects models. Additionally, we conducted 14 qualitative interviews with employees from the intervention group, which were then transcribed and analyzed for content. The training had a direct positive effect on the leaders’ well-being, but no indirect effect was observed on employees’ well-being or distress. The qualitative interviews provided insights into the changes within teams over time and offered explanations for the quantitative survey results. Our study expands the understanding of the effects of leadership training and offers insights into why an intervention might not achieve the expected outcomes for employees. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
