AB  - Reduced physical mobility is common in older adults and is associated with adverse outcomes, including functional decline, depression, social isolation, and poor nutritional status. Group-based programs focusing on physical activity and nutrition to support healthier lifestyles have demonstrated benefits, particularly when paired with social engagement activities. This paper presents the protocol for a randomized controlled trial (RCT) to test a lifestyle intervention called <b>EMBOLDEN</b> : a multifaceted intervention aimed at <b>E</b> nhancing physical and community <b>M</b> o <b>B</b> ility in <b>OLDE</b> r adults with health inequities using commu <b>N</b> ity co-design. EMBOLDEN is a co-designed 3-month intervention to improve quality of life by incorporating physical activity, healthy eating, social participation, and system navigation. Participants receiving the EMBOLDEN intervention plus usual care are expected to show improvement in physical activity and other health outcomes compared to receiving usual care alone.
