AB  - What are the interrelationships between existential concerns, worldview beliefs, and mental health? Much research has explored these connections, but often with flawed assessment measures, truncated samples, and lacking qualitative data. This study sought to further clarify this topic by using a mixed methods design and improved instruments. A sample of n = 450 United States adults was collected from various social media sites, including several forums/communities dedicated to dialogue about religions/beliefs. The sample was diverse in age (ranging 18–89), belief status (one-third nonreligious), socioeconomic status, and mental health. This mixed methods exploratory study employed an online survey battery including the Death Anxiety Beliefs and Behaviors Scale, the Existential Concerns Questionnaire, the Monotheist and Atheist Beliefs Scale, and the Hospital Anxiety and Depression Scale, as well as five qualitative essay prompts. Intercorrelations between indices of angst/dread, monotheism/atheism, and anxiety/depression are presented for both the whole sample and religious versus secular subsamples. Quantitative findings included religiosity positively associated with death anxiety, belief confidence negatively associated with distress, and existential distress positively associated with psychopathology. Qualitative themes included denial of relevance and connection between these variables, endorsement of the belief confidence/doubt effect, crucial impact of boundary situations, and metamorphoses of evolving beliefs. This project lends evidence to the belief confidence effect, contrasts with many prior studies by showing a positive link between religiosity and death anxiety, psychometrically validates two new scales of death anxiety and beliefs (Death Anxiety Beliefs and Behaviors Scale and Monotheist and Atheist Beliefs Scale), and further characterizes beliefs and existential angst by incorporating thematic analysis of participants’ essays. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
