AB  - Mexican Americans are a notable segment of the U.S. population and are affected by unique contextual factors such as their immigration history, cultural values, and religious experiences. While shame is a common experience among survivors of sexual violence (MacGinley et al., 2019), there is limited research examining the experience of shame in Mexican American survivors of sexual violence. This study sought to develop a qualitative understanding of the experience of shame among second-generation Mexican American women who are survivors of sexual violence while considering how cultural context shapes their experience of shame. Ten second-generation Mexican American survivors participated in semistructured interviews. Conventional content analysis yielded seven broad clusters: (a) influence of immigration and cultural context on shame, (b) shame pervades daily functioning, (c) relational impacts of shame, (d) impact of shame on disclosure, (e) effects of marianismo on shame after sexual violence, (f) healing from shame, and (g) challenges to healing from shame. Results indicated that the effects of shame are pervasive across multiple areas of survivors’ lives, religious and cultural messages foster a context of shame, and survivors’ healing process is shaped by their bicultural context. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
