AB  - Metaphor has long been identified as a fundamental element of everyday language and thought. While there is extensive literature on commonly used metaphors in relation to cancer, their role in psychological coping is not as well understood. This article explores the relationship between metaphor and coping in participant responses to a narrative care interview—designed to support cancer patients during the posttreatment period. The present study asked how patients’ use of metaphor in the coconstructions of their illness experiences related to their coping with diagnosis, treatment, and recovery. A subsample of 20 participants were sampled purposively for heterogeneity of demographics (sex, age, ethnicity) and cancer type. A hermeneutic metaphor analysis, informed by Lakoff and Johnson’s (1980) conceptual metaphor theory, was used to identify metaphors referring to cancer and/or coping within the context of participant narratives. All relevant instances of metaphor use in interviews were tracked and coded through an iterative and collaborative coding process. This analytic strategy yielded rich depictions of the vital role metaphoric framing plays within illness narratives regarding how patients make meaning of, and cope with, cancer. The location of metaphors in this way is valuable for exploring the meaning-making dimensions of personal suffering and healing, as evident in these coconstructed first-person narratives of cancer. The implications of this study may inform better communication between patients and care providers and promote a deeper understanding of subjective experiences of those who face illness and cancer specifically. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
