AB  - Although students with children account for one in five college students in the United States, the predominant literature about them takes a deficit approach, highlighting the ways in which they fail to fit into the “traditional” student archetype and structure of higher education, rather than the ways in which they excel or the strengths they bring to their educational pursuits. To counter this narrative, this article offers a model of student-mothers’ capital, developed out of interviews with 82 student-mothers across six colleges and universities. Drawing on critical feminist theory as well as the literature that highlights women’s gendered roles and responsibilities, the model suggests that student-mothers bring five forms of capital to their pursuit of higher education: motivational, competency, agentic, relational, and navigational. This article discusses each of these unique strengths and concludes by offering ways that institutions might recognize and build upon student-mothers’ strengths to further support this population. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
