AB  - Analogies are an important tool for supporting learning. Within therapy, analogies have multiple uses including providing psychoeducation, recommending coping strategies, and reducing stigma to clients. Limited research has empirically examined the commonality of analogy use in therapeutic training, clinicians’ knowledge of analogies, and the effects of analogy use on the therapeutic process. This study aimed to (a) investigate the presence of analogies in clinical literature and (b) examine clinicians’ perceptions of analogies and their self-reported practice use. First, 15 electronically available clinical training materials were analyzed for the prevalence of analogies and coded for structural characteristics. Then, 61 clinicians read a set of three analogies and reported their familiarity with and the use of provided analogies from the clinical training materials and their personal use of analogies with clients. Investigation of treatment manuals and clinical textbooks revealed analogies are commonly included in these materials and tend to be simple and make use of real-life source concepts. Clinicians reported frequent analogy use, with more experienced clinicians reporting the highest frequency. Clinicians with a cognitive-behavioral therapy orientation and those still completing their doctoral training identified a significantly higher number of alignments within the analogies. Results demonstrate that analogies are commonly used across psychotherapeutic contexts and orientations and are available through written training materials. Future research should continue to examine analogy use in psychotherapy and, more specifically, examine differences in analogy use as a function of client demographics and the relations between analogy use and therapy outcomes. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
