AB  - Drawing from aesthetic cognitivism—the view that art engagement can foster knowledge and understanding—this study examined whether life stories about creating or interacting with art contain existential insights. Participants (N = 108) with varying levels of art expertise (e.g., no training, students, professionals) described experiences across diverse art forms (e.g., visual art, dance, music, literature). They reflected on whether these experiences generated new understanding related to authenticity and ultimate meaning. Using interpretative phenomenological analysis, we found that participants perceived a range of insights. For authenticity, themes included increases in authenticity, recognition of inauthenticity, emotional clarity, identity awareness, and connection with others. Some also reflected on what it means to be fully present. For ultimate meaning, participants described understandings related to emotional depth, transcendent connection, spirituality, mortality, change, love, and improving the world—though many reported no understanding in this domain. Quantitative comparisons showed few differences in theme prevalence across participants’ art expertise, type of art, or creation versus interaction experiences. Although inherently subjective and not objectively verifiable, these understandings may contribute meaningfully to individuals’ narrative identities, positioning art as a potential medium for existential reflection. We outline practical implications for art engagement, education, and therapy and propose hypotheses and questions to guide future research. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
