AB  - Kensho, the Zen term for enlightenment, represents a profound shift in perception and understanding of one’s true nature. This study employs a mixed-methods approach to investigate the antecedents of kensho experiences, with particular attention to Charles Berner’s self-inquiry protocol, a structured dyadic communication practice designed to facilitate profound spiritual insights. The first study involved qualitative interviews with 13 individuals who experienced a kensho while on retreat, revealing seven main categories: (a) dark night of the soul, (b) prior awakenings, (c) childhood spiritual experiences, (d) seeking, (e) trauma, (f) role of the ego, and (g) the use of psychedelics. The second study utilized qualitative comparative analysis to identify the antecedents of kensho awakenings from these categories on the same data set. The findings demonstrate that childhood spiritual experiences and prior awakenings suggest a cumulative effect where initial spiritual breakthroughs set the stage for deeper awakenings. Contrary to expectations, the study found that psychedelic use on retreat was inconsequential in predicting kensho awakenings. This research provides a novel contribution to understanding kensho by (a) integrating Berner’s self-inquiry protocol as a pathway to spiritual awakening, (b) developing a theory to predict kensho awakenings, and (c) suggesting that kensho is part of a continuous path of spiritual purification and growth, where life is seen as a series of transformative events leading to higher consciousness. These insights offer a foundation for further exploration of structured self-inquiry methods and their role in spiritual development. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
