AB  - Training the next generation of psychologists to be socially just and culturally responsive is essential to psychology education and training. This involves integrating education, research, practice, and advocacy efforts to better address the needs of populations and issues that intersect with systems of justice—including civic, human rights, and criminal–legal matters—within the profession of counseling psychology. Literature has however rarely explored counseling psychologists’ and trainees’ interests in engaging with specific justice-involved populations and issues. We contend that stigma and misconceptions about justice-related work—and its implied alignment with the profession’s values—might impact engagement. As a pilot assessment, we surveyed 260 counseling psychology students and professionals on their interest in working with populations and topics that intersect with systems of justice. Additionally, we asked participants how work related to justice-involved populations and topics align with the identity and values of the profession, and we gathered recommendations on how justice-related work can be more effectively integrated into psychology education and training. Descriptive quantitative data revealed that the population that received the most interest was victims or survivors of harm, while individuals who commit sexual offenses received the least interest. Additionally, topics pertaining to racial justice garnered the most interest, whereas topics related to law enforcement, prisons, and retributive justice attracted less attention. Qualitative data, using reflexive thematic analysis, uncovered three themes (personal and lived experience, awareness of structural oppression, and empathy and commitment to advocacy and social justice) that orient individuals toward engagement in justice-related work. We discuss implications and offer additional recommendations. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
