AB  - The COVID-19 pandemic brought about significant changes to public health measures in Canada, affecting the availability of previously in-person services and accelerating the transition to digital mental health care. This research examined the impact of COVID-19 on accessibility and delivery of mental health care from the perspective of both providers and clients across Canada, utilizing a qualitative approach. We conducted semistructured interviews with both mental health professionals (n = 20) and clients (n = 22). Thematic analysis revealed six themes: (1) fluctuation of demand for services, (2) change in available resources, (3) systemic decision making, (4) limited nonverbal information, (5) progress, and (6) creative initiatives. Findings highlight and reinforce what was learned by practitioners and clients navigating COVID-19 as well as reflect the importance of a strong mental health care system in tackling national and global crises. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
