AB  - Gender is known to be tied to affect, but research has largely focused on the negative feelings tied to conflicts between assigned sex and current gender/sex or restrictive norms. Little research has analyzed positive emotions or pleasure related to gender/sex, and even less research has investigated pleasure through a diversity-focused lens—attention to majority and minority axes of power within analysis—as experienced by cisgender heterosexual individuals who exist in normative locations. The current article aimed to understand how and if gender/sex/ual majority groups (i.e., binary, cisgender, and heterosexual people) experience pleasure because of and/or related to their gender/sex identity and expression. To test this, we asked participants (N = 59) to share positive experiences related to their gender/sex via qualitative questions in virtual focus groups. We identified four themes from analyses: (a) gender pleasure derives from within one’s self; (b) gender pleasure derives from interpersonal interactions; (c) gender pleasure derives from comparison to “the other” binary gender/sex; (d) additional social locations can impact gender pleasure. Each of these themes consisted of behaviors that could be seen as either normative or counter-normative within a Western perspective (i.e., whether or not they are stereotypical of their gender/sex). These findings situate gender/sex/ual majority groups as majorities rather than “the norm,” and thus can inform understandings of gender/sex majority peoples’ experiences of gender pleasure, as well as gender/sex norms and experiences of pleasure more generally. This article is one of a two-part report, and the first part explores gender pleasure among gender/sex/ual minority groups. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
