AB  - This study explores the psychosocial effects of participating in Islamic collective prayer (Salat al-Jama’ah) by addressing both micro- and macrolevel mechanisms. Using unobtrusive wearable technology, we investigate the impact of participation on social connectivity and psycho–physiological well-being among Muslim participants. We employed a mixed methods approach, integrating self-reports, physiological monitoring, and proxemic analysis. Fifty-six Muslim participants engaged in congregational prayers during Ramadan. Data were collected via surveys and wearable sensors (Zephyr BioHarness 3.0 and Safe Spacer) to measure heart rate variability and group interaction patterns. Analyses included salience analysis of the qualitative data; heart rate variability before, during, and after the prayer; and social network analysis based on the frequency and duration of physical interactions. Thematic analysis identified “community” and “peace of mind” as the most cited subjective benefits of participation. In line with this, analysis of physiological data revealed a significant increase in heart rate variability during the prayer, and network analysis showed that social networks became more structurally robust following the prayer. The Salat al-Jama’ah strengthens social cohesion and promotes well-being through a combination of top-down and bottom-up processes. Phenomenologically, participants value its communal and comforting aspects. Physiologically, it has an anxiolytic effect. Moreover, socially, it encourages connectivity, suggesting that this practice has tangible functions at both the individual and social levels. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
