AB  - Prevailing definitions of trauma remain ignorant toward traumatic systems of oppression, fostering cultural incompetence in research. Meanwhile, antioppressive research largely focuses on deficit narratives of single homogenous groups, neglecting the strengths of marginalized communities and intragroup differences. As such, this mixed methods study sought to combine a more inclusive trauma taxonomy and the subjectivity of cognitive-emotional processing. This study novelly compares those who experience ongoing trauma (i.e., oppression across multiple axes of identity) with trauma survivors from dominant social positions in the context of trauma-related growth (TRG). The research examines the applicability of the “talking cure” to ongoing trauma—specifically, whether self-disclosure can promote TRG in instances where the threat is ever present. Quantitative results demonstrated a parallel multiple mediation model (N = 469) in which ongoing trauma predicted TRG directly and indirectly through self-disclosure and existential annihilation anxieties. Reflexive thematic analysis (N = 14) identified sociopolitical and interpersonal barriers to self-disclosure of ongoing trauma as well as facilitators of healing. The recognition of ongoing trauma and practical implications, including the call for worldview-based model alternatives and the need for new domains of TRG, are discussed. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
