AB  - The COVID-19 pandemic significantly impacted college students, particularly those with mental health disabilities, by exacerbating existing psychological challenges and creating new barriers to academic success and social engagement. This qualitative study examines how female college students with mental health disabilities perceived the impact of the pandemic on their psychological well-being, relationships, and academic experiences. The study focuses on students who attended two rural universities in the southern United States, where access to mental health support and resources may be more limited.Guided by the biopsychosocial model, this research employs a phenomenological approach to explore the lived experiences of these college students. Semi-structured interviews were conducted to understand participants' struggles and coping mechanisms during the pandemic. The findings highlight several challenges, including increased anxiety and depression, diminished coping skills, social isolation, strained family relationships, academic disruptions, and reduced levels of physical activity. While some participants reported personal growth and strengthened relationships, others described deteriorating mental health symptoms and difficulties maintaining motivation for coursework. Participants also provided insights into the barriers they faced when attempting to access campus support and mental health services during the pandemic.The study underscores the need for institutions of higher education to expand mental health resources, improve accommodations for students with psychological disabilities and create structured social and academic support systems. Recommendations for practice include integrating mental health awareness into college resources, enhancing telehealth and in-person counseling services, and developing targeted interventions to support students in future crises.Future research should explore the long-term effects of pandemic-related stressors on students with mental health disabilities and examine how institutional policies can better address their needs in both rural and urban settings.By capturing the voices of students with mental health disabilities, this study contributes to the broader understanding of how crises impact vulnerable populations in higher education and supports fostering more inclusive and supportive college environments. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
