AB  - The article focuses on the mental health challenges faced by student-athletes at Historically Black Colleges and Universities (HBCUs), highlighting the inequitable access to mental health resources. A study involving 205 student-athletes revealed that 59% were at risk for clinical depression and 51% for anxiety, with over half reporting no prior mental health support. The research identified significant improvements in mental health symptoms among those who accessed services, while qualitative insights pointed to barriers such as lack of social support and institutional resources. The findings underscore the urgent need for culturally responsive mental health support systems within HBCUs to address these disparities. Extracted from the article
