AB  - Secondary traumatic stress (STS) is a pervasive challenge among health care professionals, necessitating effective interventions to mitigate its impact and enhance individual, team, and organizational resilience. However, many available interventions narrowly focus on individual-level behavior change (e.g., self-care practices), placing the onus on individuals and overlooking workplace and organizational factors contributing to well-being. The Stress-Less Initiative (SLI) is a novel 12-session team-based intervention designed to mitigate and address STS through intentional cultivation of social support, protective strategies, and coping skills. This study piloted SLI within a team of hospital-based health care professionals. Afterward, six participants with varying levels of SLI engagement completed semistructured interviews to assess their perceptions of implementation outcomes and individual and team-level impacts of SLI. Interview transcripts were coded deductively, and themes were categorized using Proctor et al.’s (2011) taxonomy of implementation outcomes. Identified themes related to key implementation outcomes, including appropriateness, acceptability, feasibility, adoption, fidelity, and sustainability. Participants perceived greater personal attunement to their stress levels and efficacy to self-advocate. They also described enhanced team cohesion—including increased empathy for and connection to colleagues—following team participation in SLI. Our results provide preliminary evidence of the practicality and value of implementing a strategic, team-based initiative within health care settings to support both individual and team well-being. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
