AB  - There is a significant psychological literature investigating trauma, stress, and resilience in different populations, including mental health workers, those working in humanitarian or conflict settings, and refugees. Indigenous mental health workers on the Thai–Myanmar border operate in extreme humanitarian, resource-constrained settings and the longest running civil war in the world, and can intersect all of these above populations. No research, however, has been conducted on this specific population, and research on the mental health of healthcare workers in general in Myanmar is minimal. The aim of the present study was to investigate experiences of trauma, stress, and resilience in indigenous mental health workers operating among refugee and conflict-affected populations on the Thai–Myanmar border, filling a gap in the literature. Semi-structured interviews were conducted with five mental health workers from refugee camps. Interviews were analyzed using a descriptive phenomenological method. Results: indigenous mental health workers’ confinement in camps, the wider Myanmar context, and the difficulty of their work present a situation which carries major stresses, and some trauma. The population, however, demonstrates significant resilience, by having an existentially meaningful orientation to their work and a flexible set of active coping strategies. Self-care and continued-education are examples of active coping strategies which promote resilience, and more could be done to support mental health workers in this. This is also significant as “how we can strengthen the MHPSS workforce” has been identified by a wide variety of stakeholders as the top research priority in humanitarian global health going forward. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
