AB  - Constructs of exercise group identity (e.g., “I belong to this exercise group”) and exerciser role identity (e.g., “I am an exerciser”) predict better exercise adherence. Both exerciser group and role identities are supported by exercise group participation. However, group disbandment may present a barrier to exercise for those who identify strongly with their exercise group relative to those who identify strongly with their exerciser role. This study qualitatively examines what it means for an individual to endorse both a group identity and role identity related to running. We then examine how these identity meanings were reflected in group runners’ experiences of maintaining running after group disbandment. Two researchers conducted semistructured interviews with 15 Canadian running group members. The interviews were transcribed verbatim, and reflexive thematic analysis was used to generate themes. Our results first describe how runners conceptualize their running group and runner role identities. We then depict three themes that characterize runners’ experiences of running group disbandment (struggling without the group, thriving without the group, and keeping the group alive). We draw connections between runners’ experiences of group disbandment and their running-related identities, and these findings are related to theory and research. We conclude that group exercisers who identify with both an exerciser role and as a member of an exercise group may be optimally situated to be resilient and maintain exercise in the face of challenges such as group disbandment. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
