AB  - Autonomous sensory meridian response (ASMR) is a nascent phenomenon wherein a pleasant and relaxing tingling sensation occurs in response to audio and visual triggers like whispering and close personal attention. Biophilia is the concept that humans are innately drawn to nature. Previous research has found both phenomena elicit similar physiological and emotional responses, such as decreased blood flow, pupil dilation, and positive mood recovery. The present pilot study predicted that these phenomena may be related. A mixed-methods design was implemented to explore the similarities and differences of the sensations the phenomena elicit. Twenty-two participants watched a video of ASMR and nature sounds, after which an interview was conducted. Thematic analysis with support from quantitative data showed ASMR to be more sensorially stimulating and engaging, while biophilic stimuli were more relaxing, requiring less voluntary attention. Those who preferred ASMR tended to find biophilia less purposeful, while those who preferred biophilia found ASMR exceedingly intense. Findings support the hypothesis that ASMR is akin to a flow state. ASMR susceptibility varied, while connectedness to nature was consistently high, suggesting biophilic stimuli were universally appreciated. The implications of ASMR being defined as simultaneously relaxing and stimulating are discussed, suggesting that future research consider concepts of tonic and phasic alertness to better understand its physiological underpinnings. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
