AB  - In a novel writing task, 87 participants inserted four familiar objects (possessions) in a single story. They rated the story and its interpretation on a series of 7-point scales and completed quantitative background measures related to mood state before writing, creative interests and behaviors, insight, and ways of coping. The questionnaire and story rating data were factor analyzed with a focus on correlations between story writing and background factors. A central focus of the quantitative data was a story writing factor that described the writing experience as pleasant, the story as imaginative with a moral, and the interpretation as deep and complete as well as relevant to the lives of others. This was correlated with a positive affect state, chosen objects that evoked memories, and a disposition to look inward. A qualitative analysis compared stories composed by 15 participants at the top and bottom ends of this factor. The stories composed by participants at the top end treated the four objects in a more abstract and symbolic manner and showed a greater intensity of positive and negative emotions, whereas stories from the bottom end treated objects in a concrete way with attenuated emotion in the stories. These findings suggest that successful creative story writing is more symbolic, and writers consider the shared meaning of the work. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
