AB  - Background Fatigue, sleep disturbance, and depression often co-occur during cancer treatment or with disease progression among breast cancer (BC) patients and form a symptom cluster (fatiguesleep disturbance-depression symptom cluster, FSDSC). Tai chi has been viewed as a promising intervention to manage individual symptoms, including fatigue, sleep disturbance, and depression, among BC patients; however, current evidence on symptom clusters is limited.AimThis study aimed to assess the feasibility and preliminary effects of an evidence-based Tai chi intervention on FSDSC management among BC patients.Methods The design of this doctoral research project was guided by The Medical Research Council (MRC) framework for developing and evaluating complex interventions. In phase one, an evidence-based Tai chi intervention protocol was developed and validated based on current research evidence, Traditional Chinese Medicine theories, guidelines/practice standards, and experts' consensus. In phase two, a pilot RCT was conducted to evaluate the feasibility and potential effects of the Tai chi protocol among BC patients with the FSDSC. A total of 72 BC patients with the FSDSC were randomized to either the Tai chi group or the control group. Participants in the Tai chi group received an eight-week Tai chi intervention with two 60 min sessions per week and routine care, and participants in the control group only received routine care. The Brief Fatigue Inventory (BFI), the Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI), the Hospital Anxiety and Depression Scale-Depression (HADS-D) and The Functional Assessment of Cancer Therapy-Breast (FACT-B) were used to assess the participants' fatigue, sleep disturbance, depression and quality of life (QoL), respectively. Afterward, a qualitative process evaluation was carried out to assess the participants' experiences of taking part in the pilot study and the Tai chi practice.ResultsThe pilot RCT recruited a total of 72 BC patients, and 69 of them successfully completed all the outcome assessments, yielding a high completion rate of 95.8%. The acceptability of the study questionnaires was demonstrated to be excellent among the participants, as there were missing values for only a few FACT-B questionnaire items. The Tai chi intervention protocol was found to be feasible for BC patients with FSDSC during chemotherapy (adherence rate: 86.8%). Adverse events related to the Tai chi intervention, such as minor musculoskeletal aches and pains, dizziness, and minor knee pain, were reported by a few participants, but these mild reactions were transient and tolerable and without the need for further treatment. The unadjusted GEE analysis results demonstrated that when compared with the control group and baseline, Tai chi showed significant reductions in the scores of the BFI (B= -1.34, 95%CI [-2.09, -0.60], p < 0.001), PSQI (B = -4.23, 95%CI [-5.86, -2.61], p < 0.001) and HADS-D (B = -2.55, 95%CI [-4.35, -0.75], p = 0.006), as well as a significant improvement in the FACTB total score (B = 9.77, 95%CI [0.84, 18.71], p = 0.032) at immediately post-intervention and four-week follow-up (at all p< 0.001). These results support the hypothesis that Tai chi seemed to have a significant relief on the FSDSC and improvement in the QoL. Twenty-two interviewees who finally completed the pilot RCT took part in the semi-structured interviews to share their experiences of participating in the pilot trial and practicing Tai chi. The majority of the interviewees commented that Tai chi was a convenient, low-intensity, energy-saving intervention for symptom management. Most of the interviewees expressed that the study questionnaires were easy to complete and understand. Many of the interviewees from the Tai chi group perceived that Tai chi had positive effects on improving the FSDSC, as well as overall functional status and well-being. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2024 APA, all rights reserved)
