AB  - This study explored the effectiveness, feasibility and acceptability of an adapted mindfulness program for injury recovery and as a coping strategy more globally with collegiate student-athletes within a division 1 athletic department. On average, over 200,000 injuries occur annually among collegiate student athletes (Kerr et al., 2015). Athletes who sustain an injury often experience feelings of anger, frustration, depression, and fear (Reese et al., 2012), and require general coping skills to manage this stressful process. Psychological interventions utilized with student-athletes address the psychological response to physical injury and focus on improving rehabilitation adherence. Mindfulness-based interventions may be utilized in this domain because they have potential to reduce stress of athletic injury and improve rehabilitation outcomes by increasing pain tolerance, promoting awareness, increasing acceptance, and providing individuals with tools to cope. This pilot study implemented an adapted Mindfulness-Based Stress Reduction (MBSR, Kabat-Zinn et al., 2017) protocol, titled Mindful Life, with injured collegiate student-athletes. Quantitative and qualitative data were collected before, during, and following administration of the protocol. Feasibility was assessed by obtaining estimates about the number of participants that could be enrolled, determining treatment adherence, and by documenting reasons for dropout (Leon et al., 2011; Russell et al., 2018). Acceptability was measured through questions created specifically for this study that sought to measure participants' opinions about the Mindful Life protocol (Churcher Clarke et al., 2017; Russell et al., 2018). This study was intended to inform a larger scale, clinical trial. The findings in this study suggest that it may be feasible to recruit collegiate student-athletes to participate in the Mindful Life group. In addition, findings in this study align with previous research that suggest student-athletes may accept mindfulness as a coping mechanism for stress management. This study provides evidence that student-athletes may accept the Mindful Life protocol as an intervention, more generally. This present study can be utilized to inform the practices of sports psychologists, athletic trainers, coaches, and other individuals as they work with student-athletes. In addition, this study supports current literature on the importance of studying psychological interventions with injured student-athletes and may be utilized to inform future research. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2023 APA, all rights reserved)
