AB  - A growing body of evidence demonstrates that Asian American adolescents encounter culturally related psychosocial challenges in addition to common adolescent stressors. Nevertheless, Asian American adolescents are less likely to receive mental health care compared to White, Black, and Hispanic adolescents (Anyon et al., 2014). The current studies seek to understand Asian American adolescents’ help-seeking behaviors along the problem recognition, decision to seek help, and service selection stages of the help-seeking process (Cauce et al., 2002), using a mixed method approach. Study 1 (a quantitative study) examines help-seeking preferences during times of distress for a sample of Asian American and Caucasian high school students. Results indicated that both Asian American and Caucasian adolescents prefer to seek help from informal sources like parents and peers, rather than formal sources such as therapists and school counselors. However, Asian American adolescents were significantly less likely than Caucasian adolescents to confide in an adult and significantly more likely to have no one to confide in. Study 2 (a qualitative study) explores the rationale for Asian American adolescents’ help-seeking behaviors from two focus group discussions. Findings revealed the concerns that affect Asian American adolescents’ help-seeking behaviors. Participants spoke to the impact of stigma and lack of mental health knowledge, revealed characteristics of preferred help, and described culturally specific factors such as the model minority stereotype and lack of emotional openness. Together, findings from the two studies suggest that the current mental health safety net may not be comprehensive enough for some Asian American adolescents’ culturally influenced help-seeking behaviors. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
