AB  - There are mental benefits associated with physical activity such as reduction of stress, anxiety, depression; as well as, improvements in self-esteem, cognitive functioning and improved quality of life. Despite these known benefits, research has shown that a significant number of American adults are completely sedentary; approximately one-fourth of Americans engage in physical activity, and only 50.7% meet recommended physical activity levels. Thus, physical inactivity has become one of the leading causes of global obesity in which approximately 1.4 billion individuals globally, 20 years and older, are overweight or obese and are more likely to have major-to-moderate mental health issues. Working mothers are a population at risk due to the pressures of work, children, family, and certain perceived barriers, who often tend to be physically inactive and, as a result, are at risk for becoming physically and psychologically unhealthy. With emerging modern technology, a key challenge for the field of exercise psychology is to design and effectivity implement physical activity interventions, such as persuasive technology in the form of an Internet-based accelerometer. However, little is known about the lived experiences of working mothers using persuasive technology in the form of an Internet-based accelerometer (FitbitRTM). This study used a generic qualitative methodology that provided ten emerging themes suggesting that persuasive technology in the form of an Internet based accelerometer helped 15 working mothers with a greater capacity to understand and comprehend the cognitive-behavioral strategies based on the social cognitive theory. The results of this study helped to illuminate how exercise psychologists and technology can work together to facilitate physical activity adherence and compliance for overall psychological benefits in previously physically inactive individuals. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2024 APA, all rights reserved)
