AB  - Social influences in sport facilitate and endorse body-related ideals, which impact girls’ experiences in sport. These ideals are typically communicated and perpetuated through body commentary (i.e., positive and negative comments related to one’s body) by sport stakeholders such as parents, coaches, and athletes. However, stakeholders rarely identify that they engage in body commentary and therefore understanding the context and nature of body commentary in sport is challenging. Referees may offer a unique perspective in observing how body ideals are communicated and reinforced in sport. In the present study, 13 referees were interviewed to explore their perspectives of body commentary in the sport context. Four themes were identified through thematic analysis: (a) susceptibility for all (i.e., athletes of all body types are susceptible to body commentary); (b) coupling of weight and performance (i.e., weight comments are often closely tied with performance, whereby body commentary often reflects the narrative that higher weight players are capable); (c) referees undertake some responsibility (i.e., referees perceive some responsibility by penalizing individuals who engage in body commentary; however, they acknowledge a lot of body commentary likely goes undetected); and (d) referees experience body concerns too (i.e., women referees reported concerns about officiating uniforms not designed for more feminine body shapes and pressure to manage appearance while working in sport). Based on the results, body commentary is pervasive among and directed to girls and women involved in sport, and change is needed at a systemic level to minimize body commentary and its negative effects on sport experiences. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
