AB  - Mental health (MH) is a state of well-being that allows individuals to navigate the challenges of their work and function productively in their daily life (World Health Organization [WHO], 2018). Due to the stressors and challenges coaches face, it is important to understand how coaches who are mentally healthy (i.e., flourishing; Keyes, 2002) protect and promote their MH. The purpose of this study was to investigate how flourishing Canadian university sport coaches protected and promoted their flourishing. Initially, 14 coaches completed the Mental Health Continuum-Short Form (Keyes, 2009a) and Sport Mental Health Continuum-Short Form (Foster & Chow, 2019). Seven coaches who self-reported flourishing as indicated by their scores then participated in individual semistructured interviews. Analysis followed guidelines for interpretative phenomenological analysis (Smith et al., 2009). The results showed that the flourishing coaches acted in accordance with personally created principles. These principles were balance (managing sport and nonsport demands, making time for nonsport activities), personal growth (learning, reflection), and making a difference (promoting the development of student-athletes’ personal competencies). Although these principles may be contextually specific, the results suggest that practitioners could help coaches to establish their own principles and act in accordance with them in order to promote coaches’ flourishing. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
