AB  - To provide culturally and environmentally responsive cancer care, it is important to understand the unique experiences of cancer patients who reside in rural areas. This qualitative study explored the cancer-related psychosocial experiences of rural cancer patients for the purpose of better understanding cancer-related distress in the rural context. Using content analysis of transcribed patient interviews, the author identified common themes in overall experiences. These themes included cancer, distress, social work roles, and other items specific to the rural environment. Participants discussed various subthemes, including the role of social support, helpful attributes of an oncology social worker, transportation concerns, and environmental pollutants. Recommendations for psychosocial and medical cancer care providers are discussed. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
