AB  - QUESTIONSHow do people who are obese describe their experiences with weight loss solutions? What do they think may help them to lose weight?DESIGNQualitative study.SETTINGVictoria, Australia.PARTICIPANTSConvenience and purposive sample of 76 people (mean age 47 y, 83% women) who had a body mass index >/= 30.METHODSData were collected in face-to-face or telephone interviews. Interviews were audiotaped and transcribed. Data were analysed thematically using constant comparison.MAIN FINDINGS(1) Motivations for dieting included overall health and well-being, advice from healthcare professionals, and social acceptance. One participant stated, '...I really am sticking to the diet to get this weight off so I can fit into a skirt that I want to wear.' (2) Weight loss techniques. Participants progressed from 'fad' diets as teenagers to more commercialised diets, such as Weight Watchers and Jenny Craig. For many, diet groups were a social activity shared with family and friends. Some participants felt a sense of belonging in such groups; however, groups could also reinforce low self-esteem, negative feelings, and self-blame. When diets failed, some participants tried more extreme methods, such as very low-calorie supplements and drugs. Participants who tried drugs were generally happy with their weight loss but not drug side effects. (3) Short-term and long-term effects of weight loss techniques. Most participants lost weight when dieting and felt 'euphoric' and physically 'more comfortable.' However, inability to maintain weight loss led to feelings of failure, depression, and anger. (4) Why don't diets work? Some participants felt that diets were 'unsustainable,' 'boring,' or 'too expensive'; one 'just want[ed] to be normal,' without the restrictions imposed by dieting. Many felt diets could be successful: 'They all work...when you stick to them. It's when you go off them that they don't.' Some participants blamed themselves or life events when they stopped weight loss programmes, and some felt pressure from family and friends if they lost a lot of weight: 'I got probably within 2-3 kilos of that and I had everybody around me panicking that I was too thin and not eating enough.' (5) Physical activity. Few participants used physical activity for weight loss, and most found exercise difficult because of their weight, health problems, cost, lack of time, or embarrassment. One woman, walked at 05:00 to avoid being seen by anyone. Participants found it difficult to exercise on their own and wanted someone else to motivate them. (6) What would work? Most participants felt that different approaches to weight loss would be helpful for different people; most felt that diets were effective, and few mentioned physical activity. Many found it difficult to lose weight on their own and wanted someone else, such as primary healthcare providers, to help them. Some felt that seeking help was difficult because of the stigma associated with obesity, and many felt that support programmes with other overweight people could be empowering. One participant commented, 'So it has to be about empowering bigger people to make choices that will benefit their lifestyle, their life. It shouldn't be about weight loss....'CONCLUSIONSPeople who were obese often dieted but felt that weight loss programmes should include broader lifestyle changes. They needed ongoing support to empower them to make changes.
