AB  - This article seeks to contribute to the notably scant published literature on balancing the dual roles associated with parenting and professional development in the field of psychology. The authors offer a brief review of work-family dynamics in psychology with a specific focus on changes in the field, caregiver stigma, gender issues, economic instability, and institutional challenges. As part of a larger research study, qualitative responses about experiences in these areas were solicited and coded to understand the poignant themes presented by participants. Themes included experiences in professional training, gender discrimination, lack of support or resources, a desire for greater advocacy, and contentment within pursuing family. These themes are highlighted to acknowledge the current disparities and strengths that future and early career psychologists are confronted with as they transition to their new roles while balancing family planning. Recommendations for areas of support at the individual, interpersonal, and institutional levels are presented. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
