AB  - This article will examine the nature of peak experiences in sport and how the presence of such experiences in one’s athletic career may have a significant effect on the athlete’s career transition. A substantial body of research dating back 50 years has empirically and anecdotally displayed the prevalence and power of such experiences during their careers. Much of this research has focused on the positive effect peak experiences have on the athlete’s performance and satisfaction. Typically absent from this body of research is the question of what an athlete does to navigate the potential loss of peak experiences when the outlet to offer those experiences is gone. This article will add to the previous body of literature on the nature of peak experiences in sport while simultaneously furthering the study to ask, specifically, the question of how former contact sport athletes navigate the loss of such unique experiences in retirement. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
