AB  - This qualitative study examined the perspectives of Cambodian youth survivors of sex trafficking on trauma symptomology and healing. Interviews from free listing exercises of Cambodian youth and individual interviews with U.S. NGO workers were analyzed to gain insight about the problems youth face upon arriving at Rapha House, a residential care facility in Battambang, Cambodia, as well as their understanding of healing and resilience. Responses of Cambodian youth and U.S. workers were compared and contrasted to identify any areas of commonality and differences in their understanding of symptomology and healing. Results indicated both groups identified three types of problems that emerge when Cambodian youth enter treatment: (a) negative attitudes toward treatment, (b) emotional distress (i.e., depression, anger, fear/anxiety), and (c) atypical behaviors (i.e., social isolation, poor hygiene). In response to questions pertaining to healing, participants discussed two categories: (a) internal healing (i.e., emotional processing, identity development, change in self perception), and (b) external healing (i.e., obtaining vocational and social skills). The implications of this study can be used to further develop culturally appropriate treatment to this population. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
