AB  - Given the current impact of the opioid epidemic, the high rate of mood disorders, and the significant need for mental health service providers in Appalachia, the goal of this study was to identify the needs, value, and characteristics of Appalachian cultural identity that mental healthcare providers should learn prior to working in the region. Interpretative phenomenological analysis (IPA) guided inquiry and informed the analysis of study data. Telephone interviews were conducted to collect data from healthcare providers and academic faculty working in the communities (N = 8). Four major themes emerged from the interviews: (a) lack of access to mental healthcare, (b) unique characteristics of Appalachia that influence mental healthcare, (c) strong family bonds, and (d) barriers to healthy living. Building from the 6 principles of a trauma-informed framework of care, a proposed training framework that embraces Appalachian culture is provided. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
