AB  - Background/Aims: Physical activity can reduce the risk of many preventable chronic and debilitating diseases, such as obesity, diabetes, cardiovascular disease, depression, musculoskeletal problems and some cancers. The iStep prototype (intergenerational support to encourage physical activity) has been developed by designers and researchers from Sheffield Hallam University and the University of Sheffield. It is an intergenerational social innovation aimed at improving physical activity levels. It consists of a pedometer augmented with an interactive website. Users take part in a specific walking challenge with a partner (from a contrasting generational group) to facilitate an increase in their physical activity levels. This study describes the initial testing of the istep prototype to understand its potential usability and acceptability. Methods: Two qualitative studies were conducted. The first involved focus groups, semi-structured and dyadic interviews with secondary school pupils and teachers of a local south Yorkshire school, age range 12-60 years (n=120). The second was a modified co-operative evaluation involving 10 women aged 65-80 years, from low socioeconomic groups and with differing weight status. Results: This early stage prototype evaluation showed that the pedometer was a useful motivational tool which raised awareness of physical activity levels. The website was thought to be simple and easy to use. Walking was deemed inclusive and accessible to all age groups and setting a target goal was considered beneficial. Engaging in physical activity with a partner was regarded as a good way to provide support and encouragement. Conclusions: The iStep prototype is acceptable and straightforward to use and can be incorporated into daily routines. Modifications to the website are required followed by further testing of iStep to evaluate the impact of the changes on the intended user. Further testing of the intergenerational element of iStep is also indicated. Finally there is a need to consider how the uptake of iStep will be achieved and which behavioural change strategies may be appropriate to different end users.
