AB  - Pain is the primary cause why patients with rheumatoid arthritis (RA) seek medical care. The condition of RA affects multiple structures of the skeletal system and other organ systems. Its impact is not limited to physiological structure but also psycho-social well-being is compromised because RA is without a cure. Men with RA with anti-CCP serologic rheumatoid factor are at risk for aggressive disease path and mortality. Understanding unique needs of this population enable healthcare providers to design gender and disease specific interventions to improve quality of life among these groups.The objectives are: (1) To describe rheumatoid pain from the social context of male Veterans' perspectives with aggressive RA disease, (2) To determine beliefs about male identity influenced by RA, (3) To identify objective symbols that defines the meaning of the daily pain experience, (4) To identify self-management strategies/barriers to pain management, (5) To identify present or historical depression states and describe how mood and socio-economic challenges affect perception of pain management.Method. A cross-sectional, qualitative, descriptive design was employed. Semi-structured, in-person, interviews of 12 patients (age 36-75 years) within the VA Greater Los Angeles outpatient was conducted. In-depth textual descriptions from the men were transcribed verbatim, and Grounded Theory method of data analysis was used.Results. A substantive theory emerged which comprised of three conceptual themes; (1) 'Keep Moving' was the way in which men felt they could prevent disease progression and flare-up through three activity types; physical activities, cognitive activities and socio-economic activities), (2) 'Managing Unexpected Flare-Ups' captures what it is like to live in chronic pain and unexpectedly to intense pain, (3) 'Protecting Self and Others' was another way that men adapted in order to manage their pain, engage in protecting self and manage the disease with the help of others.Conclusion. Physical activities, management of unpredicted RA flares and self-protection and others are categories that explain how men cope with their chronic RA pain. Further studies should validate this substantive theory that explains the phenomena in which men live with chronic pain.
