AB  - Despite bariatric surgery being available since the 1950s, there is a stigma associated with having this operation. As part of a longitudinal study exploring the impact of laparoscopic adjustable gastric banding (LAGB), 35 participants (aged between 25- and 58-years-old) were interviewed prior to surgery. Reasons for disclosing (or not) their surgery were explored using thematic analysis. Findings revealed 3 themes for disclosure, and 3 for nondisclosure. In addition, measurements of weight taken preoperatively and annually until 5-years post-LAGB showed that the decision to disclose (or not) surgery did not impact on the amount of weight lost in the long-term. The decision to disclose (or not) bariatric surgery is an individual’s choice which clinicians should respect. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
