AB  - Despite a growing number of residential programs to treat eating disorders, there have been few publications on the outcome data associated with this treatment modality. This study aimed to build on what is known about transition-age youth (ages 16–24 years) who access residential eating disorder treatment, provide basic outcome information, and report on resident experiences. A retrospective chart review was conducted to examine outcomes of individuals who were admitted to a Canadian residential eating disorder treatment facility over a 5-year period (2012–2017). Charts were available for 193 youth. In addition, a retrospective thematic analysis of 39 routine exit interviews with residents who completed treatment was conducted. Residents with a goal of weight restoration demonstrated significant weight gain over the course of residential treatment, and 84.6% of residents who were interviewed reported at least partial reduction in eating disorder symptoms at discharge. The role of residential treatment in the continuum of care for eating disorders is discussed. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
