AB  - Racial minority immigrant-origin individuals experience a host of complex mental health stressors and experience disparities in mental health care provision, which may be compounded by language and cultural barriers. The present study explored the perspectives of White, Euro American clinicians who work with racial minority immigrant-origin clients. Guided by an ecological framework, we were interested in exploring potential challenges and successes and related barriers and resources, respectively, that contribute to culturally competent psychotherapy practice. We used content analysis to analyze interviews from 13 participants who were seasoned clinicians with a minimum of 5 years of experience. Participants described their perceptions of internal and external factors that impacted the therapeutic relationship. Three primary domains emerged from the analysis of the data: (a) engagement with multicultural issues, (b) perceptions of the client’s experiences, and (c) experiences of the therapeutic relationship. Implications of the findings for clinical practice, training, and research are discussed. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
