AB  - The qualitative study presented in this column aimed to explicate the meaning of being overweight for adolescents attending a medical clinic for weight reduction. Three adolescents described their story of being overweight. The participants had recently completed an intervention that included nutrition and exercise as part of a structured program supported by the American Academy of Pediatrics. Their ages ranged from 16 to 18 years. The findings of this study are grounded in a rhythm of normalcy and extraordinary pressures lived in the interhuman connections of the adolescents. The ups and downs of supportive relationships with family came in the face of ostracism and social isolation from peers. The participant's stories described a diminished sense of self that is always present and related to connections with self and others. Evidence-based implications from this study include focusing on personal strengths and continuing with a plan of fitness and health, including family members in the plan of care, and attending to the ongoing story of the persistent struggle with losing weight and prejudging in relationships with others. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
