AB  - Parkinson's disease (PD) leaves no system untouched. With its growing prevalence, clinicians and researchers are beginning to understand PD's biopsychosocial-spiritual impact on the patient as well as those who share in his or her life. This phenomenological investigation looks into the lives of 10 couples living with PD. Five dominant themes emerged from the analysis, including content about their relationship and disease history, their couple relationship, the impact of PD on the self and others, their connection with resources, and strategies for survival. Overall, they preferred a multidisciplinary approach to their treatment and believed in taking an active role in their health care. Implications for mental health and medical care providers are addressed. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
