AB  - School resource officers (SROs) are often the first responders to a school-based emergency. To date there is little research that investigates what, specifically, SROs do during a crisis. One type of school crisis is a barricaded captive-taking. This study reports on the reactions of three SROs who responded to a captive-taking event in their schools. The purpose was to begin developing categories in anticipation of validating a working model for psychologists and SRO responses. A content analysis in the grounded theory tradition was used to analyze their responses. A total of 15 categories were identified that help us understand what SROs did to respond to a school captive-taking. Implications for SROs and advancing psychological practice, strengths and limitations are addressed. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
