AB  - Persuasive arguments have been made recently for rediscovering the value of idiographic data and, specifically, of introspection (Perspectives on Psychological Science, January 2009). Such data have been crucial to me in attempting to understand both aesthetics and creativity. Used with the right controls, they are not only rich in information but also valid and reconcilable with nomothetic analyses. Here I shall summarize three complementary, long-term studies. In the first, a careful selection was made of participants for diametrically opposed aesthetic tastes, who independently underwent psychodynamic interviews; the selection provided clearly contrasting dynamics that clarified and gave meaning to the idiographic data. In the second, of two professional painters with contrasting styles in painting, patterns of speech, styles of interpersonal relationships, and their Rorchach styles, were consistent with their painting; the Rorschach even predicted (blind) their painting styles. In the third and most ambitioius study, a nomothetic analysis confirmed a series of idiographic interpretations. Each of 72 participants was followed as he or she made a “work of art” from a photograph and later underwent a psychodynamic interview. The picture-making was interpreted individually in the light of the psychodynamic data. To verify the interpretations and provide a coherent picture of the whole group, the images were then clustered; if valid, the interpretations should be consistent within the image groups and different between them. This was found (and in turn verified by independent re-analysis). Seven distinct psychological approaches to image making resulted. In these studies, complementarity of idiographic and nomothetic data was sought, and equal emphasis is given to their validity and usefulness. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
